"{\"uid\": \"straitstimes.com-sport-olympic-mascots-through-the-ages-a-journey-from-1972-to-2024\", \"text\": \"Choose edition  Search  singapore  asia  world  opinion  life  business  sport  Visual  Podcasts  SPH Rewards  STClassifieds  Paid press releases  Advertise with us  FAQs  Contact us  Sign up now:Get the biggest sports news in your inbox  Mascots through the years: (clockwise from left) Paris 2024, Los Angeles 1984, Tokyo 2020 and Beijing 2008.  PHOTOS: OLYMPICS.COM  PublishedJul 24, 2024, 01:30 PM  UpdatedJul 26, 2024, 12:23 PM  Olympic mascots are symbolic figures representing the host country and its culture, introduced to engage the public and promote the Olympic spirit.  The first official mascot was Waldi, a dachshund, at the 1972 Munich Games. All the subsequent Olympics have featured unique mascots reflecting the host nation's heritage.  Here's a look at the different mascots through the years.  Munich 1972 - Waldi  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Waldi was the first official Olympic mascot. A dachshund, chosen for its qualities of resistance, tenacity and agility, which are attributes required for athletes.  \\u2022 Created by Elena Winschermann.  \\u2022 Waldi's design was inspired by a real dachshund named Cherie von Birkenhof.  Montreal 1976 - Amik  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Amik is a beaver, symbolising hard work. It is an animal considered a national symbol of Canada. The word \\\"amik\\\" means \\\"beaver\\\" in the Algonquian language.  \\u2022 Created by Guy St-Arnaud, Yvon Laroche and Pierre-Yves Pelletier, under the leadership of Georges Huel.  \\u2022 Amik's simple design with a red sash drew mixed reactions, leading to varying interpretations of its appearance.  Moscow 1980 - Misha  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Misha, a bear character associated with Russia and the Olympic Games, wears a belt with a unique design featuring the Olympic rings.  \\u2022 Created by Victor Chizhikov.  \\u2022 Misha's departure in the closing ceremony, shown as a tearful farewell, became an iconic and emotional moment.  Los Angeles 1984 - Sam  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Friendly, cheerful eagle embodying Olympic spirit, wearing a hat with the colours of the US flag.  \\u2022 Sam is an anthropomorphic bald eagle, dressed as Uncle Sam, representing American patriotism.  \\u2022 Created by C. Robert Moore, Walt Disney Productions.  \\u2022 Sam also paid homage to the ancient Olympic Games and was featured in a cartoon.  Seoul 1988 - Hodori  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Hodori is a friendly tiger, symbolising South Korean hospitality.  \\u2022 Created by Kim Hyun.  \\u2022 Hodori's name is derived from \\\"Ho\\\", meaning tiger in Korean, and \\\"Dori\\\", a diminutive for boys in South Korea.  Barcelona 1992-Cobi  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Cobi is a humanised Pyrenean mountain dog depicted in a cubist style.  \\u2022 Created by Javier Mariscal.  \\u2022 Initially controversial for its abstract design, Cobi became very popular and commercially successful.  Atlanta 1996-izzy  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Izzy is an abstract character, a computer-generated figure symbolising the future. The blue character has training shoes and five Olympic rings on its body.  \\u2022 Created by John Ryan, DESIGNefx.  \\u2022 Izzy, initially called \\\"Whatizit\\\" (later \\\"Whatizhee\\\"), faced criticism for its ambiguous form and underwent several redesigns.  Sydney 2000  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Syd, a platypus, Olly, a kookaburra, and Millie, an echidna, represent Australia's environment and heritage.  \\u2022 Created by Matthew Hatton.  \\u2022 Syd is a reference to Sydney, Olly to Olympics and Millie to the new millennium.  Athens 2004  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Sibling dolls inspired by ancient Greek toys, symbolising the connection between the ancient and modern Games.  \\u2022 Created by Spiros Gogos, Paragraph Design.  \\u2022 Their names come from Apollo (also called Phevos), the Greek god of light and music, and Athena, the Greek goddess of wisdom and protector of Athens.  Beijing 2008  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Beibei, Jingjing, Huanhuan, Yingying and Nini. The mascots are collectively known as the \\\"Fuwa\\\", meaning \\\"good-luck dolls\\\".  \\u2022 The five mascots each represent a different colour of the Olympic rings and a Chinese symbol: fish, panda, fire, Tibetan antelope, and swallow.  \\u2022 Created by Han Meilin.  \\u2022 The names of the mascots form the phrase \\\"Bei Jing Huan Ying Ni\\\", meaning \\\"Welcome to Beijing\\\".  London 2012 - Wenlock  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Wenlock's metallic appearance comes from the last drops of steel used to build London's Olympic Stadium. His headlight is inspired by London black cabs, his forehead mirrors the stadium roof, his eye is a camera lens, and he wears five Olympic-coloured bracelets. The three points on his head symbolise the podium's medal positions.  \\u2022 Created by Iris design agency.  \\u2022 Wenlock's name comes from the town of Much Wenlock in Shropshire, which inspired the modern Olympic Games.  Rio 2016 - Vinicius  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Vinicius is a blend of various Brazilian animals, symbolising the diversity of Brazilian people, culture and nature.  \\u2022 Created by Birdo Producoes.  \\u2022 Named after the famous Brazilian musician Vinicius de Moraes, who wrote the lyrics for The Girl From Ipanema.  Tokyo 2020 mascot  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 A character with traditional and futuristic elements, symbolising a fusion of tradition and innovation.  \\u2022 Created by Ryo Taniguchi.  \\u2022 The name Miraitowa combines the Japanese words \\\"mirai\\\" (future) and \\\"towa\\\" (eternity). With a blue chequered outfit, the character wears a stylised samurai-style helmet.  \\u2022 The mascot blends traditional and futuristic styles, symbolising \\\"innovation from harmony\\\", with its forehead featuring the Tokyo 2020 Games emblem - a chessboard motif of indigo-blue rectangles in three sizes.  PHOTO: OLYMPICS.COM  \\u2022 Shaped like a Phrygian cap - a symbol of freedom in French history - Olympic Phryge appears in the French tricolour (blue, white and red).  \\u2022 Represents the power of sport to change lives and lead a revolution.  \\u2022 Created by Paris 2024 Design Team.  \\u2022 Motto is \\\"Alone we go faster, but together we go farther\\\".  \\u2022 Phrygian caps are widely recognised symbols in French culture, appearing in art, institutions and everyday objects.  \\u2022 They also hold international significance as a symbol of liberty, used by freed slaves and on various emblems in North and South America.  Cultural representation:Embody host country's culture, history and values.Festive atmosphere:Create a fun, celebratory and engaging environment.Appeal to youth:Connect with children and young people, inspiring future generations.Marketing:Enhance brand recognition, promote merchandise and generate revenue.Symbolism:Represent the Olympic spirit, values and ideals (excellence, friendship and respect).Legacy:Leave a lasting impression, becoming cherished collectibles and cultural symbols.Educational tool:Teach children about different cultures and the history of the Olympic Games.Unifying force:Bring people from diverse backgrounds together in a shared experience.Emotional connection:Evoke positive emotions, creating a sense of excitement and anticipation.Global ambassadors:Promote the host country and the Olympic movement on the world stage.  Source and illustrations:Olympics.com  Olympics 2024  Olympics  France  E-paper  Newsletters  Podcasts  RSS Feed  About Us  Terms & Conditions  Personal Data Protection Notice  Need help? Reach us here.  Advertise with us    \"}"